  <h1>Common Pedestrian Accident Misconceptions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>&ldquo;Pedestrians always have the right of way.&rdquo;</h2><p>Not always. Pedestrians have the right of way in crosswalks with a walk signal, but jaywalking or crossing against traffic can create comparative fault that reduces (or in some states bars) recovery.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;The driver&rsquo;s insurance will take care of everything.&rdquo;</h2><p>Insurers want to minimize payouts. The at-fault driver&rsquo;s BIL coverage may have limits well below your actual damages ($25K minimum in many states). Know your own UM/UIM policy limits — they may be your most important source of recovery for serious injuries.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t need an attorney for a clear-fault case.&rdquo;</h2><p>Even in clear-liability cases, insurers undervalue damages. They use formulas that minimize pain and suffering. An experienced personal injury attorney typically achieves significantly higher settlements, and works on contingency so there&rsquo;s no upfront cost.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I should accept the first offer quickly.&rdquo;</h2><p>First offers are almost always low. Do not accept any settlement before you understand the full extent of your injuries — some conditions (TBI symptoms, nerve damage, PTSD) take weeks or months to manifest fully. Accepting a settlement releases all future claims.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;My UM coverage only applies if I was in my car.&rdquo;</h2><p>UM/UIM coverage protects you as a person, not just while in your vehicle. If you are struck by an uninsured driver while on foot, your own UM coverage applies. Check your auto policy — it may be your largest source of recovery in serious pedestrian accident cases.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
